<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-530-740  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 530 740.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 14 1989 v6 n32 p119(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Leading Edge offers reorganization plan for dealer approval.andO;(Leading Edge Products Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>March, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Leading Edge Products Inc. (finance).andO;Topic:     BankruptcyReorganizationDealers and AgentsStrategic PlanningCourt CasesMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Richard MarchandM;Six months after filing for bankruptcy, Leading Edge Products Inc. is puttinga reorganization plan before its dealer/ creditors for a vote.andM;The plan, which was mailed to approximately 300 Leading Edge dealersnationwide last week, calls for Daewoo Telecom Ltd. to buy the Canton, Mass.,andO;PC distributor for $16 million.andP;  The dealers are owed $12.5 million inprepaid but unfilled PC orders to Leading Edge, which filed for Chapter 11bankruptcy protection in February.andM;Approval of the reorganization plan is expected, said some dealers.andP;  To beapproved, the plan must be supported by at least half of the dealers, whohave until the end of August to return their ballots.andP;  In addition, dealerswho support the plan must represent at least two-thirds of the total debt.andP;  A13-member creditor committee has already approved the plan.andM;If the dealers approve the plan, a confirmation hearing will be held inmid-September in the U.S.andP;  Bankruptcy Court in Boston to turn the ownershipof Leading Edge over to Daewoo Telecom, a subsidiary of the South Koreanmultibillion-dollar conglomerate, Daewoo Group.andP;  Daewoo has beenmanufacturing PCs for Leading Edge for the last three years.andM;The terms of the plan call for Daewoo to give the dealers 25 percent paybackin products this year.andP;  The dealers would then receive an additional 18.75percent per year of the amount owed them in products for the next four years.andO;There is also a three-year product/cash option open to dealers that wouldlimit the total payback to 45 percent of the amount owed.andM;Although some dealers criticized the limited cash option, many said last weekthey expect the plan to be approved because it guarantees them payback oftheir prepaid orders.andP;  Also, they said, Leading Edge's reorganization mustmove quickly.andM;&quot;What we need is speed.andP;  We need this thing to happen expeditiously,&quot; said EdSessa, a Leading Edge dealer in Albuquerque, N.M., and a member of thecreditors committee.andM;With rival PC cloners aggressively soliciting dealer orders for thebig-selling fall quarter, dealers said, Leading Edge must be operatingsmoothly to compete.andO;</TEXT></DOC>